<dl id="n10031f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10031f">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10031f"> 31(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> shrine <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n10031f"> <li>FW prototext </li><li><ms href="#n10031f">MS BL 47482b-29</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:059 <a name="qA2d" href="../../ff/fdra/qda.htm#qA2d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/q/qa2d.htm#n10031f">Draft: III&sect;2A.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Il est possible que les courriers priv&eacute;s et les voyageurs pouvaient user de l&apos;asile offert par les stations, et que ces stations ne diff&eacute;raient pas beaucoup des lieux de refuge ou de repos &eacute;tablis pour les caravanes sur les routes ordinaires, fr&eacute;quent&eacute;es jusqu&apos;au milieu des d&eacute;serts. <font color="green">[It is possible that private couriers and travellers could make use of the refuge offered by stations. These stations do not differ much from places of refuge or rest, established for caravans along ordinary roads, running even into the deserts.]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) ?27</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
